==English==

===Etymology===
{{wikipedia|Britain (name)}}
{{etyl|enm}} {{term|Breteyne|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|Bretaigne|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|la}} {{term|Britannia|lang=la}}, earlier ''Brittānia''.

The Middle English term primarily referred to the duchy of [[Brittany]], in later use specified as ''Little Britain'' or ''the less Britain'', etc., imitating Middle Latin ''Britannia minor''.
The application of the simple name ''Britain'' (or ''The Britains'') to Great Britain and the British Empire is modern, dating to after the formation of the "Kingdom of Great Britain" by the Act of Union of 1707. The legend ''Brittaniarum rex'' "king of the Britains" appears on coins from the reign of George III, beginning in 1816, but modern use consciously harks back to the style of ''rex Britanniae'' "king of Britain" used in the Anglo-Saxon period (8th century, see [[bretwalda]]).

